      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Critics argue that \"original intent\" is often unknowable, allowing judges to cherry-pick historical evidence to fit modern political goals. They claim that this selective application of history is merely judicial activism disguised as fidelity to the past. However, supporters counter that *any* judicial interpretation is inherently a form of political choice, and originalism simply offers a more disciplined, objective standard than subjective judicial philosophy.",
