      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "There is no objective consensus on which approach is \"better,\" as both aim for legal stability but achieve it differently. Originalism offers a fixed anchor to the past, providing predictability by constraining judicial discretion. Conversely, living constitutionalism allows the document to evolve with society, which some argue is necessary for a modern, dynamic democracy. Ultimately, the preference depends on whether one prioritizes textual fidelity or adaptability.",
      "source": "target",
